    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1935-01-07T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1935-01-07T00:00:00-05:00" n="758"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d758">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">611.62M31/85</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Chargé in Great Britain</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Atherton</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">No. 1151</seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">London</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1935-01-07">January 7,
                            1935</date>.<lb/>[Received January 16.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: I have the honor to refer to my despatch No. 1026
                    of November 6, 1934,<note n="10" xml:id="d758fn10">Not printed.</note> and to
                    previous correspondence with respect to American commerce in the New Zealand
                    mandated territory of Western Samoa. This matter has since been mentioned on
                    several occasions to appropriate officials of the Foreign Office, and the desire
                    of the Department for an early satisfactory solution has been urged. The Foreign
                    Office has continually promised to do everything possible to expedite formal
                    action, but apparently nothing has yet been received in London from the
                    Government of New Zealand.</p>
                <p>The Embassy will continue to press the matter, as may be feasible, with the
                    Foreign Office and will keep the Department informed.<note n="11"
                        xml:id="d758fn11">Despite repeated representations in London and Wellington,
                        no definite reply was obtained prior to a British Foreign Office note of
                        June 3, 1936, transmitted by the Ambassador in Great Britain to the
                        Secretary of State, with despatch No. 2242, June 5, 1936
                        (611.62M31/96).</note>
                </p>
                <p>Respectfully yours,</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Ray Atherton</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
